Contents of file `app/Http/Controllers/Admin/PostThumbnailController.php`:

```
<?php

namespace App\Http\Controllers\Admin;

use App\Http\Controllers\Controller;
use App\Models\Post;
use Illuminate\Http\RedirectResponse;

class PostThumbnailController extends Controller
{
    /**
     * Unset the post's thumbnail.
     */
    public function destroy(Post $post): RedirectResponse
    {
        $post->update(['thumbnail_id' => null]);

        return redirect()->route('admin.posts.edit', $post)->withSuccess(__('posts.updated'));
    }
}
```

message.content:
Explanation:

- The controller method is PostThumbnailController::destroy(Post $post).
- The method updates the Post model by setting thumbnail_id to null: $post->update(['thumbnail_id' => null]); — so this endpoint unsets/removes the post's thumbnail and does not accept a request body.
- The method returns a RedirectResponse via redirect()->route('admin.posts.edit', $post)->withSuccess(__('posts.updated')); — so the HTTP response is a redirect (302 Found) to the admin post edit page for the given post and a success flash message is stored in the session.
- The route parameter is {post} and uses Laravel route-model binding to App\Models\Post; in OpenAPI it is modeled as a required path parameter "post" (an identifier for the post, modeled as integer).
- No authentication or other behaviors are present in the provided code, so they are not represented.

